{{Use British English|date=January 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}} {{Infobox cricket tournament | previous_year = 1752 | previous_tournament = 1752 English cricket season | next_year = 1754 | next_tournament = 1754 English cricket season }} 1753 was the 57th English [[cricket]] season since the earliest known [[First-class cricket#Important matches classification|important match]] was played. Details have survived of three [[First-class cricket#Important matches classification|important eleven-a-side]] and one [[single wicket cricket|single wicket matches]].
A poem, dedicated to the [[Lionel Sackville, 1st Duke of Dorset|1st Duke of Dorset]], refers to a crimson cricket ball.<ref>Hugh Barty-King, ''Quilt Winders and Pod Shavers: the history of cricket bat and ball manufacture'', MacDonald and James, 1979</ref> It may have been made by Mr Clout, whose firm was in [[Sevenoaks]] where the Dukes of Dorset reside at [[Knole House]].
== Important matches == The following matches are classified as [[First-class cricket#Important matches classification|important]]:<ref name="status" group="note">First-class cricket was officially defined in May 1894 by a meeting at [[Lord's]] of [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC) and the [[county cricket|county clubs]] which were then competing in the [[County Championship]]. The ruling was effective from the beginning of the 1895 season. Pre-1895 matches of the same standard have no official definition of status because the ruling is not retrospective and the [[First-class cricket#Important matches classification|important matches]] designation, as applied to a given match, is based on the views of one or more substantial historical sources. For further information, see [[First-class cricket]], [[Forms of cricket]] and [[History of cricket]].</ref>
{| border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" |- bgcolor="#efefef" ! width="15.0%" align="right" | date ! width="35.0%" align="left" | match title ! width="22.5%" align="left" | venue ! width="25.0%" align="left" | result ! width="2.50%" align="right" | source |- | align="right" | 6 & 7 August (M-Tu) | [[Dover Cricket Club|Dover]] v [[Dartford Cricket Club|Dartford]] <ref name=GB18/> | [[Dover]] | Dover won by 7 runs | align="right" | <ref name=ACS23>ACS, ''Important Matches'', p. 23.</ref> |- | align="right" | ''notes'' | colspan="4" | Dover scored 57 and 83; Dartford scored 95 and 38. This is the first significant mention of Dover in cricket history. Dartford remained a premier club through the 1750s so presumably this was a shock result. |- | colspan="5" | |- | align="right" | 7 & 8 August (Tu-W) | [[Hambledon Club|Hambledon]] v [[Surrey county cricket teams|Surrey]] | [[Broadhalfpenny Down]] | Hambledon won by 113 runs | align="right" | <ref>Maun, p. 38.</ref> |- | align="right" | ''notes'' | colspan="4" | Hambledon scored 202 and 105; Surrey scored 131 and 63. This is the first mention of cricket being played on Broadhalfpenny (discovered in the ''Salisbury Journal'' in 2011). John Lucas, of Portsmouth, scored 82 in Hambledon's first innings. |- | colspan="5" | |- | align="right" | 15 August (W) | Two Elevens <ref name=GB18/> | [[Artillery Ground]] | result unknown | align="right" | <ref name=ACS23/> |- | align="right" | ''notes'' | colspan="4" | This was a benefit match for Mr Anderson of the Dial in Long Alley, Moorfields. There was a well-known player called [[William Anderson (18th-century cricketer)|William Anderson]], first mentioned in 1745, so possibly this was he. The two elevens were made up of various players from the general London area with "the best bowlers to be parted". |- | colspan="5" | |- | align="right" | 30 August (Th) | [[London Cricket Club|London]] v Marylebone <ref name=GB18/> | [[Artillery Ground]] | result unknown | align="right" | <ref name=ACS23/> |- | align="right" | ''notes'' | colspan="4" | Marylebone (no connection with MCC) had [[Tall Bennett]] and [[William King (London cricketer)|William King]] as given men. |- |}
==Single wicket== ''Monday, 10 September''. [[London Cricket Club|Two of London]] were to play [[Tom Faulkner]] and [[Joe Harris (cricketer)|Joe Harris]] for £20 at the [[Artillery Ground]].<ref name=GB18>[[G B Buckley]], ''Fresh Light on 18th Century Cricket'', Cotterell, 1935</ref>
