{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}} {{Infobox non-profit | name = Cricket for Change | image = Cricket for Change.png | type = | founded_date = 1981 | tax_id = | registration_id = | founder = | location = <!-- this parameter modifies "Headquarters" --> | coordinates = | origins = | area_served = | product = | mission = | focus = | method = | revenue = | endowment = | num_volunteers = | num_employees = | num_members = | subsid = | owner = | non-profit_slogan = | former name = | homepage = http://www.cricketforchange.org.uk/cricket-for-change | dissolved = | footnotes = }} '''Cricket for Change''' (C4C), registered as the London Community Cricket Association, is a UK charity established in 1981 to provide support for young disadvantaged people to be able to take part in cricket events. Programmes include providing cricket facilities, training, disabled access to cricket,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/intouch_20081028.shtml |title=BBC Radio 4 – In Touch |publisher=BBC News |date=28 October 2008 |accessdate=2010-08-19}}</ref> establishing cricket projects in deprived inner-city estates and providing coaching and practical support for other charities internationally.
==Awards== * 2009 Andy Dalby-Walsh (C4C Director of Programmes) winner of ''Pride of Britain Feelgood Factor Award''.<ref>[http://www.itv.com/lifestyle/thismorning/more/prideofbritainawards2009/ This Morning | Pride of Britain Awards 2009 – ITV Lifestyle<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> * 2010 [[Israel Cricket Association]]’s ''Cross Border Cricket Programme'' in partnership with C4C awarded the Europe Pepsi ICC Development Award for ''Best Spirit of Cricket Initiative''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.icc-europe.org/DATABASE/ARTICLES/articles/000053/005370.shtml |title=ICC Europe announces Regional Winners of Pepsi ICC Development Programme Awards for 2009 |publisher=Icc-europe.org |date= |accessdate=2010-08-19}}</ref><ref name=Hall/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricketforchange.org.uk/international/israel |title=Our International Initiatives |publisher=Cricketforchange.org.uk |date= |accessdate=2010-08-19}}</ref><ref name=BBC20090426>{{Cite news |title=Cricket breaks down Israel boundaries |last=Franks |first=Tim |date=26 April 2009 |newspaper=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/8016943.stm}}</ref> * 2010 Adam Hall (C4C Development Manager – North London)<ref name=BBC20050916>{{Cite news |title=London: Sport not guns |last=Limbajee |first= Khevyn |date=16 September 2005 |newspaper=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/politics_show/4246556.stm}}</ref> wins ''National Young Coach of the Year''.<ref name=Hall>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cricketworld.com/countries/england/community_cricket/article/?aid=23031 |title=Cricket For Change Wins More Awards |publisher=Cricketworld.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-19}}</ref>
==Inner-city projects== C4C's projects to support cricket for inner-city areas has wide recognition,<ref name=BBC20080715 >{{Cite news |title=Bopara for radical Twenty20 plan |last=Dirs |first=Ben |date=15 July 2008 |newspaper=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/7507598.stm}}</ref> in particular for young people who may be vulnerable to becoming involved in crime. The charity has contributed to the Government's [[Home Affairs Select Committee]] due to its track record in supporting crime prevention.<ref>{{Cite web|author=The Committee Office, [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/cgi-bin/newhtml_hl?DB=semukparl&STEMMER=en&WORDS=cricket%20chang&ALL=%22Cricket%20for%20Change%22&ANY=&PHRASE=%22%22cricket%22%20%22change%22%22&CATEGORIES=&SIMPLE=&SPEAKER=&COLOUR=red&STYLE=s&ANCHOR=muscat_highlighter_first_match&URL=/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmhaff/242/10020904.htm#muscat_highlighter_first_match |title=House of Commons – Home Affairs Committee – Minutes of Evidence |publisher=Publications.parliament.uk |date=9 February 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-19}}</ref>
==International projects== In 2008 and 2009 C4C were guests of the Israel Cricket Association, to work in and around [[Beersheba]], near the Gaza border. The project was to start initiatives for "Street20 cricket" using plastic bats and wickets and a tennis ball wrapped in electrical tape.<ref name=israel>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/where-theres-a-willow-crickets-pitch-for-peace-in-the-holy-land-20090413-a4t9.html |title=Cricket for Change goes to Gaza strip |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=14 April 2009 |first=Duncan |last=Campbell |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref> {{quotation|Last year's trip included a visit to [[Hura]], a [[Bedouin]] settlement in the [[Negev desert]]. "We went into the playground and within 10 minutes there were about 50 kids playing. "They loved it and they said they wanted to play with Jewish kids."|Spokesperson for C4C,<ref name=israel/>|2009}}
The [[United States of America Cricket Association]] partnered with C4C to establish [[Blind cricket]] in the USA in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more_sports/2010/02/14/2010-02-14_andy_dalbywelsh_other_blind_cricket_players_show_big_apple_the_possibilities.html |title=Andy Dalby-Welsh, other blind cricket players show Big Apple the possibilities |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=14 February 2010 |accessdate=2010-08-19 | first=Mark | last=Lelinwalla}}</ref>
